    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nWhen new events are added, they often lead to bugs because the event wasn't tested for unexpected script actions such as: \r\n\r\n- switching the current buffer/window/tabpage\r\n- editing the buffer contents\r\n- deleting the current, or previous, buffer/window/tabpage\r\n    - `:bdelete`, `:bwipeout`, ...\r\n- resizing windows\r\n- creating new windows\r\n- closing windows\r\n- shelling out via `system()`\r\n- attempting to open cmdwin\r\n\r\nHere's one example of such test coverage, though it's missing many of the other cases mentioned above: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/83037cf2185704a4b9a93c0883dc93226de86fdc/test/functional/autocmd/markset_spec.lua#L192\r\n\r\n## Proposal\r\n\r\n`testnvim.lua` should provide a generic `setup_evil_autocmd` or `assert_weird` which makes it easy for new events to use this util function to gain test coverage for these edge cases.\r\n\r\n_Originally posted at https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/25134#issuecomment-4060478473_",
